[[File:Yoshida Jinja Mitoshi Torii.jpg|220px|thumb|<center>Ichino Torii</center>]]
'''Yoshida Shrine'' (Yoshida Shrine) is located in {{ill|lt=Ibaraki Prefecture|Q83273|WD=Q83273|1=Ibaraki Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Mito City|Q204249|WD=Q204249|1=Mito, Ibaraki}} Miyauchi Town. {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinai|1=UNKNOWN}} ({{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), {{ill|lt=Hitachikuni|Q1055353|WD=Q1055353|1=Hitachi Province}}{{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|lt=Sannomiya|1=Ichinomiya}}, {{ill|lt=modern company rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=old company rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural company|1=UNKNOWN}}.

=== Overview ===
It is located on top of Mt. Asahi, a small hill in the southern part of central Mito city. Its founding tells of {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|WD=Q461258|lt=Nippon Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru}}'s involvement in the eastern expedition. Because it enshrines the god of war, Japan Takeru, it is a shrine that has long been highly revered by the Imperial Court during the {{ill|lt=Ezo|Q932574|WD=Q932574|1=Emishi}} conquest process. Although the shrine building was burnt down in the war, a place related to Nihon Takeru still remains within the precincts as ``Mt. Sankaku.''

=== Enshrined God ===
The enshrined deity is one of the following<ref name="Yoshisho">Shrine Historysho. </ref>.
* '''{{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|WD=Q461258|lt=Nippon Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru}}''' (Yamato Takeru Mikoto)
*: The 12th {{ill|lt=Emperor Keiko|Q329723|WD=Q329723|1=Emperor Keikō}} prince and father of the 14th {{ill|lt=Emperor Chuai|Q179971|WD=Q179971|1=Emperor Chūai}}. According to "{{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|WD=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}" and "{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|WD=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}," he subjugated the powerful clans of Kyushu and eastern regions on the orders of Emperor Keiko.

=== History ===

=== Founding ===
According to ``Joyo Shikinai Chinza Honki'' and ``Hitachi Twenty-eight Shrine Considerations,'' it is said that {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|WD=Q461258|lt=Nippon Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru}} rested his soldiers at this place (Mt. Asahi/Mt. Misumi) during his eastern expedition, and the shrine was built in honor of this {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikinai Shrine)|1976}}. The date of its establishment is unknown, but according to ancient documents in the possession of Yoshida Shrine, it was enshrined in {{ill|lt=Shoan|Q1327427|WD=Q1327427|1=Shōan}}4 ({{ill|lt=1301|Q5610|WD=Q5610|1=1301}}). There is a note stating that more than 800 years have passed {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}[http://www.yoshidajinja.jp/hist.html]. The regular autumn festival held on October 19 and 20, 1985 was held as a celebration of the 1500th anniversary of the founding of the company.<ref>Iharaki Shimbun, morning edition of October 21, 1985. </ref>. The location of the shrine's resting place is still told today in a corner of the temple grounds.

Concerning this tradition, there is a theory that the connection to Nihon Takeru dates back to the early {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, since there is no story about Nippon Takeru in Naga District in ``{{ill|lt=Hitachikuni Fudoki|Q11481687|WD=Q11481687|1=Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki}}'' {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Gods)|1984}}.

=== Outline ===
First seen in national history is {{ill|lt=Jowa (Japan)|Q1075605|WD=Q1075605|lt=Jōwa|1=Jōwa (Heian period)}} In 13 years ({{ill|lt=846|Q30454|WD=Q30454|1=846}}), he was ranked as a junior fifth rank, lower rank, and eighth rank. It is written that ``Yoshida God'' in } was listed as {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha #Meishin Name|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|lt=Meishin|1=Myōjin Taisha}} {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}. After that, the divine rank was {{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} first year ({{ill|lt=857|Q30374|WD=Q30374|1=857}}), and was given the rank of Junior Fourth Rank, Lower Rank, and Eighth Rank, {{jalink|Jōgan}. (Japan)|Q1075635|Jōgan}}5 years ({{ill|lt=863 years|Q25052|WD=Q25052|1=863}}) Junior Fourth Rank, Upper Rank 8th Class, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Genkei|1=UNKNOWN}}2 ({{ill|lt=878|Q23910|WD=Q23910|1=878}}), he was promoted to Seishi Rank, Lower Rank, 8th Class {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}.{{ill|lt=extension (era name)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Extended|1=Enchō}} "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" established in 5 years ({{ill|lt=927 years|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) {{ill|lt=In the Engishiki Shrine Name Book|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shin Name Book|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, "Yoshida Shrine It is listed as {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}{{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikinai Shrine)|1976}}. In addition, Yoshida Shrine is {{ill|lt=Kashima Shrine|Q706499|WD=Q706499|1=Kashima Jingū}} ({{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|1=Ichinomiya}}) in Hitachi Province, {{ill|lt=Shizukami It is said to have been ranked as the third shrine after Shri|Q11663648|WD=Q11663648|1=Shizu Shrine}} (Ninomiya), and was built in the year 2000, following Kashima Shrine {{Sfn|Ichinomiya system|2000|p=233}}. The reason why it was ranked 3rd in Hitachi Province and 1st in Naka District (Naka District) is said to be due to its relationship with Japan Takeru, the enshrined god of war, and the Ezo conquest, as well as its relationship with the decline of the Ujibe clan in Naga District, which was dominant in the west of Mito.{{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Taira)|1982}}In the Middle Ages, ``Yoshida County'' was separated from Naga County as the {{ill|lt=Kamigun|Q11590937|WD=Q11590937|1=Kamigun}} of Yoshida Shrine, but the territory of Yoshida Shrine was 158 towns, covering half of Yoshida County {{Sfn|Yoshida County (Taira)|1982}}. From then on, this shrine territory strengthened its character as a manor, and was also called ``Yoshida Manor'' {{Sfn|Yoshida District (Taira)|1982}}. In addition, we call Yakuo-in Temple {{ill|lt=Jingu-ji|Q1074971|WD=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}}, and it is said that the shrine had 6-ken and 3-ken corridors, torii gates, and tamagaki, as well as many attached buildings and subsidiary shrines {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Taira)|1982}}, and that the shrine reached the rank of Shoichii {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikinai Shrine)|1976}}. After that, Yakuo-in flourished as the center of {{ill|lt=Tendai sect|Q668188|WD=Q668188|1=Tiantai}}, controversy increased, and the divine power declined {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Taira)|1982}}.

During the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, he was deeply revered by the {{ill|lt=Mito domain|Q1146904|WD=Q1146904|1=Mito Domain}}, especially {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Mitsukuni Tokugawa|1=UNKNOWN}} repaired the main shrine, worship hall, and many other shrine buildings in {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}}6 ({{ill|lt=1666|Q7585|WD=Q7585|1=1666}}).{{Sf n|Yoshida Shrine (Taira)|1982}}, {{ill|lt=Nariaki Tokugawa|Q1323770|WD=Q1323770|1=Tokugawa Nariaki}} was founded in {{ill|lt=Tenpo|Q1369045|WD=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}}15 ({{jalink {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Gods)|1984}} who donated ``{{ill|lt=Dainippon History|Q1156003|WD=Q1156003|1=Dai Nihonshi}}'' and 100 koku shrine territory to |1844|Q7633}}.After {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, in April of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was ranked as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural shrine|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}} in {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}.

In {{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}20 ({{ill|lt=1945|Q5240|WD=Q5240|1=1945}}), the entire shrine building was burnt down in an air raid {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}. The shrine building was rebuilt in 1948 ({{ill|lt=1948|Q5165|WD=Q5165|1=1948}}), and has undergone subsequent renovations and repairs to its current state {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}.

=== God level ===
