=== Shinto priest ===
Yoshida Shrine's social affairs are said to have been handled by ``Kimikoji'' in ancient times {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Taira)|1982}}. The origin and personality of the Yoshimi-kou clan are not clear, but it is said that he belonged to the Emishi tribe in the early Nara period, and there is also a theory that points to a deep relationship with the Emishi {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Gods)|1984}}. After that, Mr. Yoshimiko was appointed to the Central Government during the {{ill|lt=Chojo|Q1194264|WD=Q1194264|1=Chōshō}} years ({{ill|lt=1132|Q19582|WD=Q19582|1=1132}}-{{ill|lt=1135|Q19594|WD=Q19594|1=1135}}). {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Taira)|1982}}{{Sfn|Yoshida District (Taira)|1982}} who donated a social affairs position (Ryoke position) to the family'''{{ill|lt=Otsuki clan|Q11462133|WD=Q11462133|1=Ozuki clan}}'''. This donation is said to have been made to protect the shrine's territory from the interference of local government officials and the invasion of local clans {{Sfn|Yoshida District (Taira)|1982}}. 

Through subsequent changes, there were five former shrine families (the Tadokoro clan, the Akutsu clan, the Sakaki clan, the Watanabe clan, and the Inoue clan) before the Meiji period. After the Shake system was abolished by the Constitution of the Empire of Japan, the Tadokoro clan was in charge until the middle of the Meiji period, and the Akutsu clan thereafter. After the enactment of the Religious Corporations Law after the war, the Akutsu clan was in charge until the early Heisei period after passing through several Shinto priests, and the Tadokoro clan is currently in charge.

=== Precincts ===
The main shrine has {{ill|lt=Shinmei-zukuri|Q930545|WD=Q930545|1=Shinmei-zukuri}} copper plate roofing, and the worship hall and the shrine have {{ill|lt=irimoya-zukuri|Q855025|WD=Q855025|1=East Asian hip-and-gable roof}} copper plate roofing, both of which were rebuilt after the war {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}.

On the approach to the shrine, there is a place consecrated as the ``Asahi Sankakuyama Ruins'' where the enshrined deity Nihon Takeru rested {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}. This triangular mountain is said to be the site of the main shrine and rituals {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Gods)|1984}}.

