=== Betsugu ===
[[File:Kasahara-koyasu-jinja haiden.JPG|thumb|200px|right|<center>Kasahara Yasu Shrine (Kasahara Town)</center>]]
[[File:Sakado-jinja (Mito) haiden.JPG|thumb|200px|right|<center>Sakamon Shrine (Sakamon Town)</center>]]
"Shuhachisha Ryakuenshi" describes Kasahara Daimyojin and Sakamon Daimyojin as separate shrines.

; Kasahara Yasu Shrine (Kasahara Daimyojin)
:* Enshrinement location: Ichiban, Kasahara-cho, Mito City ({{Coord|36|21|5.17|N|140|27|18.13|E|region:JP-08_type:landmark|name=Bekku: Kasaharayasu Shrine}})
:* Deities enshrined: {{ill|lt=Ototachibanahime|UNKNOWN|lt=younger brother Tachibanahime}}, {{ill|lt=Konohanasakuyahime|UNKNOWN|lt=Konohanasakuyahime}}: A separate shrine of Yoshida Shrine and one of the seven shrines in Mito. During the {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} years ({{ill|lt=1661|Q7005|WD=Q7005|1=1661}}-{{ill|lt=1673|Q7617|WD=Q7617|1=1673}}), a shrine was built at the current location on the orders of the founder of the Mito domain, {{ill|lt=Yorifusa Tokugawa|Q1133680|WD=Q1133680|1=Tokugawa Yorifusa}}, and it was said to be the guardian deity of safe childbirth. It is said that there was a tradition of borrowing a statue from the head office when giving birth, and then returning it and offering it after a safe delivery. The offspring were Chinami, Mikawa, and Kasahara. Kasahara Shrine became a religious corporation in September 1952 ({{ill|lt=1952|Q5272|WD=Q5272|1=1952}}), and is now known as ``Kasahara Yasu Shrine'' under the jurisdiction of the umbrella organization {{ill|lt=Shinja Honcho|Q908077|WD=Q908077|1=Association of Shinto Shrines}}.
: According to the documents owned by Yoshida Shrine, on February 24, {{ill|lt=Enkei (Japan)|Q1327068|WD=Q1327068|lt=Enkei|1=Enkyō (Kamakura period)}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=1309|Q5726|WD=Q5726|1=1309}}), the then Saemon-jo and Uemon-jo issued a reply regarding ``Yoshida Kasahara Shrine Transfer Shrine.'' Furthermore, on May 25, 1996 ({{ill|lt=1396|Q6405|WD=Q6405|1=1396}}), Ujiyoshi Sani sent out a letter of donation stating, ``Kasahara Gosha Gotodensho Hōdonoya'' (from ``Suifu Geion Koroki'').

; Sakamon Shrine (Sakamon Daimyojin)
:* Enshrinement location: Sakamon-cho, Mito City ({{Coord|36|21|22.47|N|140|29|52.64|E|region:JP-08_type:landmark|name=Bekku: Sakamon Shrine}})
:* Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Konohanasakuyahime|UNKNOWN|lt=Konohana Sakuyahime}}

=== Precincts Suesha ===
* Rokusha (on the right side facing the main shrine)
** Matsuo Shrine - A branch of {{ill|lt=Matsuo Taisha|Q710302|WD=Q710302|1=Matsunoo Taisha}} in {{ill|lt=Kyoto|Q740246|WD=Q740246|1=Kyōto}}.
** Taga Shrine - A branch of {{ill|lt=Taga Taisha|Q402091|WD=Q402091|1=Taga-taisha}} in {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|lt=Shiga|1=Shiga Prefecture}}.
** Sumiyoshi Shrine - A branch of {{ill|lt=Sumiyoshi Shrine|Q11381857|WD=Q11381857|1=Sumiyoshi Shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Osaka|Q11439906|WD=Q11439906|1=Ōsaka}}.
** Hachiman Shrine - A branch of {{ill|lt=Hachiman Shrine|Q11390939|WD=Q11390939|1=Hachiman shrine}}.
** Okunishushi Daishu Shrine - Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Okunishu no Mikoto|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Okunishushi no Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}, {{ill|lt=Kotoshiro no Mikoto|Q8009611|WD=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshiro no Mikoto|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}}.
** Small Pox Guardian Shrine

* Two shrines (back right facing the main shrine)
*: A simple shrine building built with a terraced structure. Both companies are mentioned in the ``Chinjucho'' and ``Jinhachisha Ryakuenshi.''
** Kunimi Shrine - Enshrined deity: Hikokuni Mikaki Kenyotsuka no Mikoto. {{ill|lt=Ise Jingu|Q687168|WD=Q687168|1=Ise Grand Shrine}}He is the enshrined deity of Geku Setsusha and {{ill|lt=Watari Kunomi Shrine|Q11486118|WD=Q11486118|1=Watarai Kunimi Shrine}}, and the ancestor of Ise Kunizo and Watarai Shinto priests.
** Hayatoshi Shrine - Enshrined deity: Ryodoirihime no Mikoto. One of the wives of Takeru of Japan and the mother of Emperor Chuai.

* Two shrines (back left facing the main shrine)
*: A simple shrine building built with a terraced structure. Both companies are mentioned in the ``Chinjucho'' and ``Jinhachisha Ryakuenshi.''
** Ii Shrine - Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Emperor Chuai|Q179971|WD=Q179971|1=Emperor Chūai}}. He was the second prince of Japan Takeru, and his mother was Ryodo Irihime no Mikoto.**: "Shingusha" is written in "Chinjucho". The ``Shuhachisha Ryakuenshi'' describes it as ``Ii Shrine'' and ``Kehi Myojin''.
** Mito Shrine - Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko|UNKNOWN|lt=Hayaakitsuhiko no Mikoto}}. A branch of Mito Shrine in Kasahara-cho, Mito City.

* Two shrines (Kodaijingu Shrine and Toyouke Daijingu Shrine)
*: "Shuhachisha Ryakuenshi" says "Ise Nisho Bekku". A branch of {{ill|lt=Ise Jingu|Q687168|WD=Q687168|1=Ise Grand Shrine}}{{ill|lt=Kōtai Jingu|Q11581011|WD=Q11581011|lt=Naiku|1=Kōtai Jingū}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Geku|1=UNKNOWN}}. The shrine building is Nigensha {{ill|lt=Shinmei-zukuri|Q930545|WD=Q930545|1=Shinmei-zukuri}}.
** Kodai Shrine - Enshrined Deity: {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu}}.
** Toyouke Daijingu Shrine - Deity enshrined: {{ill|lt=Toyouke Hime|UNKNOWN|lt=Toyouke Hime no Mikoto}}.

* Inari Shrine/Hashi Shrine
*: In "Shuhachisha Ryoenshi", it is only described as {{ill|lt=Inari God|Q719665|WD=Q719665|lt=Inari Myojin|1=Inari Ōkami}}. A simple shrine building built with a terraced structure.

* Hoshimiya Shrine
* Tenmangu - Enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Michizane Sugawara|Q382005|WD=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}
*: ``Chinjucho'' says ``Tenjin Shrine,'' and ``Shuhachisha Ryakuenshi'' says ``Tenma Tenjin.'' While all the other subsidiary shrines have small shrine buildings, Tenmangu Shrine has a medium-sized, flowing-style shrine building with a well-maintained place of worship.

=== Festival ===
A list of festivals held annually at Yoshida Shrine <ref name="Yoshisho"/>.
* Monthly festival (1st and 15th of every month)
* New Year's Day Festival ({{ill|lt=January 1st|Q2150|WD=Q2150|1=January 1}})
* Setsubun Festival ({{ill|lt=February 3rd|Q2315|WD=Q2315|1=February 3}})
* Open-air tea ceremony (around late March)
* Spring Festival ({{ill|lt=April 29th|Q2535|WD=Q2535|1=April 29}})
* Great Purification ({{ill|lt=June 30th|Q2657|WD=Q2657|1=June 30}})
* Rice planting festival, children's andon festival (late July)
* Reitaisai (mid-October)
*: In the old days, it was held on {{ill|lt=September 15th (lunar calendar)|Q840070|WD=Q840070|lt=September 15th of the lunar calendar|1=September 15 (Lunisolar)}}. A grand mikoshi crossing to the Naka River is held {{Sfn|Yoshida Shrine (Gods)|1984}}.
* Shichi-Go-San prayer (during November)
* Labor Thanksgiving Day ({{ill|lt=November 23rd|Q3021|WD=Q3021|1=November 23}})
* Great Purification ({{ill|lt=December 31st|Q2912|WD=Q2912|1=December 31}})

